["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"ROBERT","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":12,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":21,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When SIR ROBERT LATIMER was born in 1316, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Latimer, was 41 and his mother, Joanna de Govis, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Catherine de Hull. He died on 28 August 1361, in Pulham, Dorset, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1316–28 August 1361":"1316–28. august 1361","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1316–1361":"1316–1361","1318–Male":"1318–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1325–1361":"1325–1361","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1355–1443":"1355–1443","1275–1317":"1275–1317","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1275":"1275","1 May 1346":"1. mai 1346","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1355":"1355","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","28 August 1361":"28. august 1361","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Buckland Newton, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Buckland Newton, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pulham, Dorset, England":"Pulham, Dorset, England","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1316–28 August 1361":"1316–28. elokuuta 1361","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1316–1361":"1316–1361","1318–Male":"1318–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1325–1361":"1325–1361","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1355–1443":"1355–1443","1275–1317":"1275–1317","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1275":"1275","1 May 1346":"1. toukokuuta 1346","1285":"1285","1361":"1361","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1346":"1346","1355":"1355","1443":"1443","145